datasets.name: Targeting endothelial cell to macrophage communication in NF1 tumors
datasets.description_clean: Targeting endothelial cell to macrophage communication in NF1 tumors Targeting endothelial cell to macrophage communication in NF1 tumors CTF - Drug Discovery Initiative Registered Reports Principal Investigator: Brian Stansfield Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Brian Stansfield Institution: Augusta University Project Description: We will use three established animal models of angiogenesis and tumor growth to assess the efficacy of imipramine in suppressing pathologic angiogenesis and tumor growth. For all three models, littermate lysmCre+ and lysmCre- Nf1 flox/flox mice will be randomized 1:1 to vehicle or imipramine (7mg/kg/day). In the oxygen-induced retinopathy model, P7 pups will be subjected to 70% oxygen for 5 days and returned to normoxia for 5 days. Retinal flat mounts, single cell suspensions, and lysates will be used to assess avascular and neovascular area and quantify macrophage and endothelial cell content. In the hind limb ischemia model, 8-10 week old male and female littermates will undergo right femoral artery ligation and serial doppler ultrasound to assess collateralization over time. We will also employ micro-CT to quantify capillary density in both limbs. In the orthotropic tumor model, AT3 mouse breast tumor cells will be injected into mammary pads of 8 week old female littermates and tumor growth will be monitored using bioluminescent imaging and immunohistology. Innovation: This application is innovative on many levels: 1. First use of a novel macropinocytosis in translational animal models 2. Targeting intercellular communication to suppress angiogenesis and tumor growth 3. Seeks efficacy data in more than one tumor-relevant model Impact: If our hypothesis is correct and imipramine suppresses pathologic angiogenesis and tumor formation, we will be able to quickly move imipramine into Phase I/II human clinical trials for neurofibromas and MPNST as well as other NF1 manifestations for which macrophages are critical to disease pathogenesis. datasets.name: Leveraging the PN drug screen to identify targets in Noonan Syndrome
datasets.description_clean: Leveraging the PN drug screen to identify targets in Noonan Syndrome --- Team The ExTUMORnators Team Members: --- Noonan syndrome (NS) is a common genetic disorder that causes multiple congenital abnormalities and predisposes to different tumors. Gene mutations leading to the hyperactive Ras signalings have been reported as the driving forces for NS. Plexiform neurofibromas (PN), NS, Costello syndrome, cardio-facio-cutaneous syndrome, and Legius syndrome are grouped clinically as Rasopathies. They share certain symptoms and the Ras/mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK) pathway is all elevated. Specifically, the NS patients have an increased chance to develop malignant tumors, however, there is no systematic drug screen or drug target study published in this field yet. Hack4Rare 2021 provides a platform that enables the integrated study for Rasopathies. Here, we want to leverage the PN drug screen data to identify potential drug targets in NS by defining the conserved signaling and gene regulation networks among the two disorders. We hypothesize that drugs targeting the converse gene regulation networks between PN and NS cell models can serve as candidates for NS. To further narrow down the drug candidates, 1) the drug response data in PN were correlated to the preserved gene networks and then grouped according to the similar patterns among all drug candidates to generate drug clusters. 2) Genes that are annotated as drug targets within a specific drug cluster and genes within a preserved network were analyzed by gene ontology (GO) enrichment, respectively, and the similarities between the enriched GO terms in a gene network and a drug cluster were computed using semantic analysis to confirm relevant biology. High GO similarity indicates high relevance between the drug and conserved gene regulation network. 3) An actionable drug list was ranked according to the correlation between the networks and drug responses. datasets.name: IGF1 deficiency integrates stunted growth and neurodegeneration in Down syndrome
datasets.description_clean: Collection of datasets included in: IGF1 deficiency integrates stunted growth and neurodegeneration in Down syndrome Paula Araya, Kohl T. Kinning, Christina Coughlan, Keith P. Smith, Ross E. Granrath, Belinda A. Enriquez-Estrada, Kayleigh Worek, Kelly D. Sullivan, Angela L. Rachubinski, Kristine Wolter-Warmerdam, Francis Hickey, Matthew D. Galbraith, Huntington Potter, and Joaquin M. Espinosa Cell Reports 2022 Dec 27;41(13):111883 PMID 36577365 doi: 10.1016/j.celrep.2022.111883 Abstract Down syndrome (DS), the genetic condition caused by trisomy 21 (T21), is characterized by stunted growth, cognitive impairments, and increased risk of diverse neurological conditions. Although signs of lifelong neurodegeneration are well documented in DS, the mechanisms underlying this phenotype await elucidation. We report here a multi-omics analysis of neurodegeneration and neuroinflammation biomarkers, plasma proteomics, and immune profiling in a diverse cohort of 400+ research participants. We identified depletion of IGF1, a master regulator of growth and brain development, as the top biosignature associated with neurodegeneration in DS. Individuals with T21 display chronic IGF1 deficiency downstream of growth hormone production, associated with a specific inflammatory profile involving elevated TNFa. Shorter children with DS show stronger IGF1 deficiency, elevated biomarkers of neurodegeneration, and increased prevalence of autism and other comorbidities. Altogether, these results point to disruption of the IGF1 liver-brain axis as a contributor to stunted growth and neurodegeneration in DS. datasets.name: Somatic Mosaicism in the Brain of Tourette Syndrome
datasets.description_clean: NDA Data Source: Data from Labs. Data from Labs are 'NDA Collections', which contain datasets from one grant or project.   Tourette Syndrome (TS) is a disorder of the developing telencephalon for which no significant causative genetic variant has yet emerged through the examination of blood samples. In this proposal we investigate whether somatic mutations might underlie in part the pathogenesis of TS. Existing evidence suggests that cells accumulate somatic mutations after the formation of the zygote, implying that cells of the human body do not have identical DNA sequence. Besides single nucleotide variation (SNV) and small insertion/deletions (InDels), cells can accumulate copy number variations (CNVs, i.e., duplications and deletions), insertions of transposable elements, inversions and translocations, all involving from few hundred to several millions of nucleotides. Somatic mosaicism arising in brain cells could explain the failure to discover consistent, replicable genetic risk factors in neuropsychiatric disorders like TS, and underlie at least in part the frequently observed variability between blood genotype and overall phenotype. There is no estimate of somatic mosaicism in either normal development or in disease. To test the hypothesis that somatic mutations might underlie the emergence of TS, in this proposal we will discover and quantify somatic genome variation in TS and normal control brains, followed by exploration of potential functional consequences of this variation. datasets.name: Acute Communication Between Microglia and Nonparenchymal Immune Cells in the Anti-AB Antibody-Injected Cortex
datasets.description_clean: Publication links: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11780351/ https://www.jneurosci.org/content/45/5/e1456242024 Abstract Anti-Aβ immunotherapy use to treat Alzheimer's disease is on the rise. While anti-Aβ antibodies provide hope in targeting Aβ plaques in the brain, there still remains a lack of understanding regarding the cellular responses to these antibodies in the brain. In this study, we sought to identify the acute effects of anti-Aβ antibodies on immune responses. To determine cellular changes due to anti-Aβ antibody exposure, we intracranially injected 14 mo APP male and female mice with anti-Aβ IgG1 (6E10) or control IgG1 into the cortex. After 24 h or 3 d, we harvested the cortex and performed a glial cell-enriched preparation for single-cell sequencing. Cell types, proportions, and cell-to-cell signaling were evaluated between the two injection conditions and two acute timepoints. We identified 23 unique cell clusters including microglia, astrocytes, endothelial cells, neurons, oligos/OPCs, immune cells, and unknown. The anti-Aβ antibody-injected cortices revealed more ligand-receptor (L-R) communications between cell types, as well as stronger communications at only 24 h. At 3 d, while there were more L-R communications for the anti-Aβ antibody condition, the strength of these connections was stronger in the control IgG condition. We also found evidence of an initial and strong communication emphasis in microglia-to-nonparenchymal immune cells at 24 h, specifically in the TGFβ signaling pathway. We identify several pathways that are specific to anti-Aβ antibody exposure at acute timepoints. These data lay the groundwork for understanding the brain's unique response to anti-Aβ antibodies. Citation: Foley, K. E., et al. (2024). "Acute communication between microglia and non-parenchymal immune cells in the anti-Aβ antibody injected cortex." The Journal of Neuroscience: e1456242024.

datasets.name: Multi-omics profiling of Sjogrens Syndrome
datasets.description_clean: Whole blood gene expression, serum proteome, and peripheral peripheral immunophenotype measured from patients with primary Sjögren’s syndrome and healthy controls. Multi-omics study was conducted to elucidate the crucial molecular mechanisms of primary Sjögren’s syndrome (SS) pathology. We generated multiple data set from well-defined patients with SS, which includes whole-blood transcriptomes, serum proteomes and peripheral immunophenotyping. Based on our newly generated data, we performed an extensive bioinformatic investigation. Our integrative analysis identified SS gene signatures (SGS) dysregulated in widespread omics layers, including epigenomes, mRNAs and proteins. SGS predominantly involved the interferon signature and ADAMs substrates. Besides, SGS was significantly overlapped with SS-causing genes indicated by a genome-wide association study and expression trait loci analyses. Combining the molecular signatures with immunophenotypic profiles revealed that cytotoxic CD8 ­T cells­ were associated with SGS. Further, we observed the activation of SGS in cytotoxic CD8 T cells isolated from patients with SS. Our multi-omics investigation identified gene signatures deeply associated with SS pathology and showed the involvement of cytotoxic CD8 T cells. These integrative relations across multiple layers will facilitate our understanding of SS at the system level. Tasaki S, Suzuki K, Nishikawa A, Kassai Y et al. Multiomic disease signatures converge to cytotoxic CD8 T cells in primary Sjögren's syndrome. Ann Rheum Dis 2017 Aug;76(8):1458-1466. PMID: 28522454 Link to jornal

datasets.name: Epilepsy in Parry-Romberg Syndrome and Linear Scleroderma En Coup De Sabre Spectrum Diseases
datasets.description_clean: -> Epilepsy in Parry-Romberg Syndrome and Linear Scleroderma En Coup De Sabre: Case Series and Systematic Review of the Literature Alison M. Hixon, PhD, Elijah Christensen, PhD, Robert Hamilton, MD, Cornelia Drees, MD > Principal Investigator : Cornelia Drees, MD Citation pending Abstract Parry-Romberg syndrome (PRS) and linear sclerosis en coup de sabre (LScs) are rare, related, autoimmune conditions of focal atrophy and sclerosis of head and face which are associated with the development of focal epilepsy. The scarcity of PRS and LScs cases has made an evidence-based approach to optimal treatment of seizures difficult. Decades of data within case reports and series, however, offer insights into improving care. Here we present a large systematic review of the literature evaluating 137 cases of PRS or LScs, as well as three new cases with epilepsy that span the spectrum of severity, treatments, and outcomes in these syndromes. Analysis showed that intracranial abnormalities and epileptic foci localized ipsilateral to the external (skin, eye, mouth) manifestations by imaging or EEG in 92% and 80% of cases, respectively. Epilepsy developed before external abnormalities in 19% of cases and after external disease onset in 66% of cases, with decreasing risk the further from the start of external symptoms. Importantly, 55% of cases achieved seizure freedom and 29% reported seizure improvement during the time frame reported. Of these, 27% achieved seizure control with only one anti-seizure medication (ASM), 29% needed to trial more than one ASM, 31% improved on immunomodulatory therapy (IMT), and 10% controlled seizures successfully with surgery. All data have been deposited in a Synapse.org database for ongoing case tracking with the potential for international collaboration. We hope this information and database will serve to guide neurologists caring for these patients. Literature Database For information on and access to the publicly available literature database, clic

datasets.name: Triplication of the interferon receptor locus contributes to hallmarks of Down syndrome in a mouse model
datasets.description_clean: Collection of datasets included in: Triplication of the interferon receptor locus contributes to hallmarks of Down syndrome in a mouse model Waugh KA, Minter R, Baxter J, Chi C, Galbraith MD, Tuttle KD, Eduthan NP, Kinning KT, Andrysik Z, Araya P, Dougherty H, Dunn LN, Ludwig M, Schade KA, Tracy D, Smith KP, Granrath RE, Busquet N, Khanal S, Anderson RD, Cox LL, Estrada BE, Rachubinski AL, Lyford HR, Britton EC, Fantauzzo KA, Orlicky DJ, Matsuda JL, Song K, Cox TC, Sullivan KD, Espinosa JM Abstract Down syndrome (DS), the genetic condition caused by trisomy 21, is characterized by variable cognitive impairment, immune dysregulation, dysmorphogenesis and increased prevalence of diverse co-occurring conditions. The mechanisms by which trisomy 21 causes these effects remain largely unknown. We demonstrate that triplication of the interferon receptor (IFNR) gene cluster on chromosome 21 is necessary for multiple phenotypes in a mouse model of DS. Whole-blood transcriptome analysis demonstrated that IFNR overexpression associates with chronic interferon hyperactivity and inflammation in people with DS. To define the contribution of this locus to DS phenotypes, we used genome editing to correct its copy number in a mouse model of DS, which normalized antiviral responses, prevented heart malformations, ameliorated developmental delays, improved cognition and attenuated craniofacial anomalies. Triplication of the Ifnr locus modulates hallmarks of DS in mice, suggesting that trisomy 21 elicits an interferonopathy potentially amenable to therapeutic intervention. PMID: 37277650 DOI: 10.1038/s41588-023-01399-7 Analysis Details Poly-A(+) RNA enrichment, and strand-specific library preparation were carried out using a Universal Plus mRNA Kit Poly(A) (Tecan/Nugen). Paired-end, 150 bp sequencing was carried out on an Illumina NovaSeq 6000 instrument by the Genomics Shared Resource at the University of Colorado Anschutz Medical Campus. RNA-seq data yield was a minimum of 30 million

datasets.name: Early developmental asymmetries in cell lineage trees in living individuals
datasets.description_clean: NDA Data Source: Data from Papers. Data from Papers are 'NDA Studies', which contain analyzed data from one or more NDA Collections (datasets from a grant or project).   Post-zygotic mosaic mutations can be used to track cell lineages in humans. By using cell cloning and induced pluripotent cell lines (iPSC), this study analyzed early cell lineages in a phenotypically normal individual and an individual living with Tourette syndrome, and a postmortem human specimen. A minimally invasive framework for defining cell lineages in any living individual was established, which paves the way for studying their relevance in health and disease. Provided through this study is whole genome sequencing data of iPSC lines, and from blood, saliva, urine from the living individuals and multiple brain regions and spleen from the postmortem specimen. DATA ACCESS Data for this study is being made available through the NIMH Data Archive study 930

datasets.name: Multidimensional definition of the interferonopathy of Down syndrome and its response to JAK inhibition.
datasets.description_clean: Collection of datasets included in: Multidimensional definition of the interferonopathy of Down syndrome and its response to JAK inhibition Matthew D Galbraith, Angela L Rachubinski, Keith P Smith, Paula Araya, Katherine A Waugh, Belinda Enriquez-Estrada, Kayleigh Worek, Ross E Granrath, Kohl T Kinning, Neetha Paul Eduthan, Michael P Ludwig, Elena W Y Hsieh , Kelly D Sullivan, Joaquin M Espinosa Abstract Individuals with Down syndrome (DS) display chronic hyperactivation of interferon signaling. However, the clinical impacts of interferon hyperactivity in DS are ill-defined. Here, we describe a multiomics investigation of interferon signaling in hundreds of individuals with DS. Using interferon scores derived from the whole blood transcriptome, we defined the proteomic, immune, metabolic, and clinical features associated with interferon hyperactivity in DS. Interferon hyperactivity associates with a distinct proinflammatory phenotype and dysregulation of major growth signaling and morphogenic pathways. Individuals with the highest interferon activity display the strongest remodeling of the peripheral immune system, including increased cytotoxic T cells, B cell depletion, and monocyte activation. Interferon hyperactivity accompanies key metabolic changes, most prominently dysregulated tryptophan catabolism. High interferon signaling stratifies a subpopulation with elevated rates of congenital heart disease and autoimmunity. Last, a longitudinal case study demonstrated that JAK inhibition normalizes interferon signatures with therapeutic benefit in DS. Together, these results justify the testing of immune-modulatory therapies in DS. Publication details + URL Science Advances. 2023 Jun 28;9(26):eadg6218. PMID: 37379383 PMCID: PMC10306300 DOI: 10.1126/sciadv.adg6218 Analysis Details Samples should be matched across datasets at the level of LabID (ie blood draw) and not RecordID (participant).

datasets.name: A syndrome-level composite resistance index to inform the use of empiric antibiotic therapies
datasets.description_clean: A syndrome-level composite resistance index to inform the use of empiric antibiotic therapies Summary Antibiotics are most often prescribed empirically to treat infection syndromes before the causative bacteria and their susceptibility to antibiotics are confirmed . The effectiveness of antibiotic therapies is compromised by the emergence and spread of antibiotic-resistant bacteria . Hence guidelines on empiric antibiotic therapy are a key component of current clinical care for infection syndromes and must be informed by knowledge of bacterial resistance. In this work, we used the ATLAS dataset to derive a composite index of antibiotic resistance for common infection syndromes. We argue that this could be a more clinically relevant measure of resistance, as opposed to reporting resistance rates for individual pathogens, to inform on the appropriateness of empiric antibiotic therapies. We developed a framework that integrated data on antibiotic prescribing guidelines, aetiology of infections, access to and cost of antibiotics, with antibiotic susceptibility from global antimicrobial resistance (AMR) surveillance datasets to derive this index. The results are presented in an interactive web app to allow users to visualise underlying resistance rates to first-line empiric antibiotics for their infection syndromes and countries of interest. We conclude that the ATLAS dataset, in its current form, is not suitable to inform empiric antibiotic therapies for many syndromes but that a framework like ours will be useful going forward with increasing coverage and improved sampling of antibiotic resistance surveillance. datasets.description_clean: The CSBC U01 Research Project \@ Vanderbilt List of Collaborating Institutions   Project Websites https://labnodes.vanderbilt.edu/community/profile/id/334 https://my.vanderbilt.edu/lopezlab/   Project Description The goal of our U01 project to develop rational systems approaches to treat cancer. Small-cell lung cancer (SCLC) is arguably the most aggressive form of lung cancer, and while modern treatment strategies are initially highly effective, tumors quickly relapse, resistant to further therapies. We seek to decode the gene-regulatory processes that underlie SCLC’s phenotypic response to treatment, and develop clinically viable strategies to reprogram those circuits, while keeping cells locked into drug-sensitive states. Our major driving questions are: How does SCLC heterogeneity contribute dynamic adaptation to treatment? What regulatory mechanisms govern this response, and how are they coordinated? How can these regulatory mechanisms be manipulated to drive SCLC cells toward therapeutically desirable phenotypes? What molecular species can be targeted therapeutically to affect these mechanisms? To this end we will integrate bioinformatics, mathematical modeling, and experimentation to provide a systems-level understanding of SCLC drug response and optimal treatment strategies.   -><- Available Resources Project Investigators Vito Quaranta, M.D. Vito Quaranta, M.D. is the Director of the Quantitative Systems Biology Center, and Professor of Cancer Biology at Vanderbilt University School of Medicine. In children with neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1), genetic mutations affecting the RMK pathway lead to multisystemic disorder, including measurable effects on behavior and cognition. Mainly, NF1 increases the risk of deficits in attention, hyperactivity, and social skills. While the effects of NF1 on human brain structure and function are evident, their usability as outcome measures is limited. Using high-resolution structural MRI, diffusion-weighted imaging, resting-state fMRI, (neural correlates) and a targeted battery of cognitive-behavioral assessments, we will first assess the neural correlates of, and cognitive-behavioral features associated with attentional and social dysfunction in children with NF1 relative to controls. Then, we will leverage recent advances in brain imaging techniques and computational methods; we will assess the effect of NF1 on the organization and coupling of large-scale structural and functional brain networks. datasets.description_clean: This dataset includes X chromosome exome sequencing data generated from two families with a previously undescribed lethal X-linked disorder of infancy; the disorder comprises a distinct combination of an aged appearance, craniofacial anomalies, hypotonia, global developmental delays, cryptorchidism, and cardiac arrhythmias. Using X chromosome exon sequencing and a recently developed probabilistic algorithm aimed at discovering disease-causing variants, we identified in one family a c.109T>C (p.Ser37Pro) variant in NAA10, a gene encoding the catalytic subunit of the major human N-terminal acetyltransferase (NAT). A parallel effort on a second unrelated family converged on the same variant. The absence of this variant in controls, the amino acid conservation of this region of the protein, the predicted disruptive change, and the co-occurrence in two unrelated families with the same rare disorder suggest that this is the pathogenic mutation. We confirmed this by demonstrating a significantly impaired biochemical activity of the mutant hNaa10p, and from this we conclude that a reduction in acetylation by hNaa10p causes this disease. Here we provide evidence of a human genetic disorder resulting from direct impairment of N-terminal acetylation, one of the most common protein modifications in humans. datasets.name: Identification of modifier genes in LZTR1-associated schwannomatosis by whole exome sequencing
datasets.description_clean: Identification of modifier genes in LZTR1-associated schwannomatosis by whole exome sequencing Identification of modifier genes in LZTR1-associated schwannomatosis by whole exome sequencing CTF - Contract Award Principal Investigator: Laura Papi Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Laura Papi Institution: University of Florence Project Description: Schwannomatosis is a tumor-predisposition syndrome characterized by the adult onset of multiple schwannomas (benign tumors of the nerve covers). A significant fraction of schwannomatosis patients harbors germline mutations in SMARCB1, a gene located on chromosome 22. More recently, another chromosome 22 gene, named LZTR1, has been found mutated in a number of SMARCB1-negative SCH patients. However, in our cohort of LZTR1-associated patients and their relatives, only 34 out of 60 mutation carriers of a pathogenetic LZTR1 variant were affected. Our working hypothesis is that a modifier gene, carried exclusively by patients and not by their unaffected relatives, is responsible of the schwannomatosis phenotype. The project focuses on the sequencing of the coding part of the genome (the so-called exoma) in LZTR1 mutation carriers, affected and unaffected, from unrelated Italian families. Thereby, the main objective is the identification of gene(s) that can modify the schwannomatosis phenotype. In conclusion, the revaluation of LZTR1-mutated families may lead to the identification of different inheritance model(s), able to explain variable expressivity of schwannomatosis. The discovery of the molecular mechanism/s underlying schwannomatosis might lead to the development of new medical approaches to improve clinical management and quality of life of affected patients. datasets.description_clean: Global protein changes associated with Chr8 gain in MPNST Global protein changes associated with Chr8 gain in MPNST CTF - Young Investigator Award Principal Investigator: Simge Acar Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Simge Acar Institution: Washington University in St.Louis Project Description: Neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) is an autosomal dominant tumor predisposition syndrome with a prevalence of 1:2500-3000 worldwide. Individuals with NF1 begin life with one inactivated and one functional copy of the NF1 gene in every cell in their body. MPNST is a clinically aggressive cancer arising from schwann cells which of the peripheral nerves. Despite surgical resection, radiation, and chemotherapy, MPNST recur in almost 50% of individuals, and most people die within five years of diagnosis. A better understanding of these aggressive cancers is imperative to improve new therapeutic approaches. We previously analyzed genomic changes in MPNST and a set of PN, and found that MPNST had extra copies of large pieces of DNA (called chromosomes) and loss of other chromosomes, whereas the PN samples had the normal number of each of these chromosomes. We will investigate this through two specific aims. In Aim 1, we will investigate the global changes that occur in cells with Chr8 gain. To do this, we will use cells that have NF1 loss and an extra copy of chromosome 8 (Chr8gain cells) compared to cells that have only NF1

datasets.description_clean: Full title: Genomics based analysis of interactions between developing B-lymphocytes and stromal cells reveal complex interactions and two-way communication In order to identify extra cellular signals that promote B lymphocyte development we created a database with approximately 400 receptor ligand pairs and software matching gene expression data from two cell populations to obtain information about possible communication pathways. Using this database and gene expression data from NIH3T3 cells (unable to support B cell development) and OP-9 cells (strongly supportive of B cell development) and data from pro-B and pre-B cells as well as mature peripheral B-lineage cells, we were able to identify a set of potential stage and stromal cell restricted communication pathways. Functional analysis of some of these potential ways of communication allowed us to identify BMP-4 as a potent stimulator of B-cell development in vitro. Further, the analysis suggested that there existed possibilities for progenitor B cells to send signals to the stroma. The functional consequences of this were investigated by co-culture experiments revealing that the co-incubation of stromal cells with pro-B cells altered both the morphology and the gene expression pattern in the stromal cells.

datasets.description_clean: A Preclinical Trial Pipeline of Neuroprotective Agents for Vision Loss in NF1-OPG A Preclinical Trial Pipeline of Neuroprotective Agents for Vision Loss in NF1-OPG GFF - Vision Restoration Initiative Principal Investigator: Yunshuo Tang Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Yunshuo Tang Institution: Washington University in St. Louis Project Description: Neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) is a cancer predisposition syndrome that affects 1 in every 3,000 children around the world. Children with NF1 are prone to developing benign and malignant tumors of the nervous system. One of the most common tumors affecting children with NF1 is optic pathway glioma (OPG), a slow-growing tumor of the visual pathway that can cause retinal ganglion cell (RGC) death and vision loss. Currently, children with NF1-OPG are treated with chemotherapy, which, while effective at limiting tumor growth, is not very effective at protecting or restoring vision. In an effort to reduce vision loss in children with NF1-OPG, our laboratory has worked extensively to identify several new therapies that showed potential for protecting vision in Nf1 mice with optic pathway glioma. Now we will subject these promising treatments to rigorous preclinical trials to determine whether they are safe, effective, and able to achieve long-lasting vision protection. NF Data Curator App

datasets.description_clean: Preclinical Therapeutic Evaluation of ALY101 in a murine model of neurofibromatosis type 2 Preclinical Therapeutic Evaluation of ALY101 in a murine model of neurofibromatosis type 2 CTF - Drug Discovery Initiative Registered Reports Principal Investigator: Wade Clapp Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Wade Clapp Institution: Indiana University Project Description: Neurofibromatosis Type 2 (NF2) is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by haploinsufficiency of the NF2 gene that encodes the tumor suppressor protein, Merlin. The NF2 disease is a tumor predisposition syndrome and bilateral vestibular schwannomas (VS) are pathognomonic for the disease. VS can cause hearing loss or deafness, vestibular dysfunction, and compression of vital structures, including the brainstem and cerebellum. Currently, there are no FDA-approved therapies for NF2 and treatment often involves surgical resection of the tumors. Our lab has developed a genetically engineered mouse (GEM) model of NF2 using Cre-Loxp system to excise NF2 in the neural crest using the 3.9kbPeriostin promoter. This model closely recapitulates the human disease progression. The NF2 GEM develops paraspinal schwannomas, VS, and progressive hearing loss. Furthermore, we and others have identified p21 activated kinase 1 (PAK1) as a promising therapeutic target to combat this disease, however previous attempts at inhibiting PAK1 have resulted in simultaneous inhibition of PAK2, resulting in cardiotoxicity. Alyra Therapeutics, Inc. has developed a novel PAK1 inhibitor, ALY101, which blocks the binding of both RHOJ and CDC42 to PAK1, thereby inhibiting PAK1 while also avoiding off-target inhibition of PAK2 and other kinases. We hypothesize that ALY101 will successfully reduce tumor burden and hearing loss in our mouse model of NF2. NF Data Curator App

datasets.description_clean: The ROSMAP iPSC-Derived Induced Neurons (ROSMAP-IN) Study This study generated whole transcriptome and proteomic data for iPSC derived neurons from a curated set of "Religious Order Study" (ROS) and "Memory and Aging Project" (MAP) subjects across a spectrum of Alzheimer’s Disease (AD) pathologies. iPSC generation Each iPSC line is given a BRID line name (i.e. “BR09”), that maps to ROSMAP subject IDs. Peripheral blood mononuclear cell (PBMC) samples from the ROS and MAP cohorts were first expanded in StemPro-34 SFM Complete Medium (Thermo Fisher,10639-011) supplemented with cytokines SCF (100ng/mL, R&D Systems, 255-SC-050), Flt3 (100ng/mL, R&D Systems, 308-FK-025/CF), IL3 (20ng/mL, Cell Signaling, 8918SF), and IL6 (20ng/mL, Cell Signaling, 8904SC) for 4 days to enrich for myeloid and erythroblast lineages and to generate samples for sterility testing by Chocolate Agar or SteriTEC sterility assays, cell line ID fingerprinting with SNPtrace genotyping panel (Fluidigm, PN100-6280], and to prime cells for reprogramming. Primed PBMC samples passing sterility tests were seeded at either 30k or 50k cells/well in a 96-well Cultrex (HESC qualified Cultrex, Trevigen, 3434-001-02) coated plate for reprogramming using CytoTuneTM-iPS Sendai Reprogramming v2.0 Kit (Thermo Fisher, A16517) per the manufacturer’s recommendations modified for cell number and plate format. In some cases, primed PBMCs were first frozen into barcoded Matrix tubes (Thermo Fisher, 50823819) in Synth-a-freeze Cryopreservation Media (Thermo Fisher, A125542) before reprogramming. After infection, cells were gradually transitioned to Freedom media (DMEM-F12 with Freedom-1 Supplement, Life Technologies, Custom) for 5 days post- infection with partial daily media changes on the NYSCF Global Stem Cell Array® platform. Live cell surface staining using the iPSC marker Tra-1-60 (Tra-1-60 Antibody, Life Technologies) was performed 12-14 days post-transfection to identify reprogrammed cells. Successfully reprogrammed

datasets.description_clean: Full title: Genomics based analysis of interactions between developing B-lymphocytes and stromal cells reveal complex interactions and two-way communication In order to identify extra cellular signals that promote B lymphocyte development we created a database with approximately 400 receptor ligand pairs and software matching gene expression data from two cell populations to obtain information about possible communication pathways. Using this database and gene expression data from NIH3T3 cells (unable to support B cell development) and OP-9 cells (strongly supportive of B cell development) and data from pro-B and pre-B cells as well as mature peripheral B-lineage cells, we were able to identify a set of potential stage and stromal cell restricted communication pathways. Functional analysis of some of these potential ways of communication allowed us to identify BMP-4 as a potent stimulator of B-cell development in vitro. Further, the analysis suggested that there existed possibilities for progenitor B cells to send signals to the stroma. The functional consequences of this were investigated by co-culture experiments revealing that the co-incubation of stromal cells with pro-B cells altered both the morphology and the gene expression pattern in the stromal cells.

datasets.description_clean: Comments on "DCC manual on scientific metadata" This is a very lengthy manual, and already somewhat dated (2011). Ch 2 Chapter 2 has an interesting and entertaining introduction to "the scientific method", the role and methods of communication in science, An important point made is that scientific communication is crucial for scientific progress. Data, and the exchange thereof, in turn is crucial in the communication between scientists. And for data to be searchable and understandable, metadata is required. Ch 3 Discusses metadata. Scientific metadata, as discussed above, documents and annotates scientific datasets, providing the auxiliary information necessary to find, interpret, understand, assess and use them. Metadata is most often in pairs: keyword-value. If the metadata is based on a fixed scheme (agreed upon by arbitrary group of users) both keywords and values may be defined as elements of some vocabulary/ontology. But (scientific) metadata often contains free text elements to accommodate those funky stubborn scientists. key/value pairs can specify: purely descriptive/qualitative digital representation of the data (format, size, location, etc) auxiliary information necessary to interpret the data Inclusion of physical quantities in metadata also requires definitions and units. datasets.description_clean: Rotor syndrome is an autosomal recessive disorder characterized by conjugated hyperbilirubinemia, near-absent hepatic uptake of anionic diagnostics, and coproporphyrinuria. The mechanistic basis of other hyperbilirubinemia syndromes is largely understood, but that of Rotor syndrome has remained enigmatic. The existing paradigm of hepatic bilirubin excretion postulates a unidirectional elimination pathway: Uptake of conjugated bilirubin from blood by hepatocytes, glucuronidation of bilirubin, and excretion of conjugated bilirubin into bile by ABCC2, a canalicular bilirubin-glucuronide and xenobiotic export pump. An analogous view holds for drugs conjugated in the liver. Here we demonstrate by molecular-genetic analysis of 8 Rotor-syndrome families that Rotor syndrome is a two-gene disorder, with impaired hepatic re-uptake of bilirubin-glucuronide caused by complete deficiencies in the hepatic organic anion transporting polypeptides OATP1B1 and OATP1B3.

It is characterized primarily by tumors of the nervous system, but in addition, cognitive disabilities and autistic features are highly prevalent. Up to 50% of patients experience these learning disabilities, and often suffer substantial social communication deficits. However, it remains unknown how these deficits occur, and there are currently no effective treatments. NF1 patients have mutations in the neurofibromin 1 gene, resulting in loss of function of the neurofibromin 1 protein. Neurofibromin 1 normally serves as a key regulator of another protein, Ras, which is responsible for cell growth. Without a functional neurofibromin protein to regulate Ras in NF1 patients, cells divide in an uncontrolled manner, leading to tumors. In contrast to the tumorigenic symptoms of NF1, little is known about the molecular and cellular basis of social behavioral differences. To gain new insights into the mechanisms of these pervasive deficits, and ultimately identify treatment targets, animal models of social processing in NF1 are needed. Mouse, Zebrafish, and Drosophila models exhibit many of the behavioral phenotypes observed in humans, and studies of this kind have led to important insights regarding signaling pathways and drug discovery. However, there have been no established animal models of NF1-dependent social deficits, until now. Recent work from the Kayser lab has characterized impaired social behaviors in Nf1 mutant Drosophila. There are numerous benefits to studyin

datasets.name: GSE13948
datasets.description_clean: Antagonism of microRNA-122 in mice by systemically administered LNA-antimiR leads to up-regulation of a large set of predicted target mRNAs in the liver MicroRNA-122 (miR-122) is an abundant liver-specific miRNA, implicated in fatty acid and cholesterol metabolism as well as hepatitis C viral replication. Here, we report that a systemically administered 16-nt, unconjugated LNA (locked nucleic acid)-antimiR oligonucleotide complementary to the 5 end of miR-122 leads to specific, dose-dependent silencing of miR-122 and shows no hepatotoxicity in mice. Antagonism of miR-122 is due to formation of stable heteroduplexes between the LNA-antimiR and miR-122 as detected by northern analysis. Fluorescence in situ hybridization demonstrated uptake of the LNA-antimiR in mouse liver cells, which was accompanied by markedly reduced hybridization signals for mature miR-122 in treated mice. Functional antagonism of miR-122 was inferred from a low cholesterol phenotype and de-repression within 24 h of 199 liver mRNAs showing significant enrichment for miR-122 seed matches in their 3 UTRs. Expression profiling extended to 3 weeks after the last LNA-antimiR dose revealed that most of the changes in liver gene expression were normalized to saline control levels coinciding with normalized miR-122 and plasma cholesterol levels. Combined, these data suggest that miRNA antagonists comprised of LNA are valuable tools for identifying miRNA targets in vivo and for studying the biological role of miRNAs and miRNA-associated gene-regulatory networks in a physiological context. Keywords: compound treatment

datasets.description_clean: Human methyl-CpG-binding protein 2 (MeCP2) disruption causes Rett syndrome, an autistic disease prevalent in females. Previous microarray expression profiling studies using tissue homogenate samples from mouse model of the Rett syndrome revealed only modest changes in expression caused by the loss of Mecp2, making it difficult to identify etiology of the Rett syndrome. Here, we carried out cell type specific genome wide expression profiling of Mecp2 null mice in three neuronal cell types. We found a hot spot of Mecp2 affected genes in chromosome 11B3 syntenic to human chromosome 17p13 which has known associations to mental retardation. We also found Mecp2 affected genes are almost non-overlapping between cell types. Cell-adhesion category of genes, however, are commonly overrepresented, suggesting a possible etiology of Rett syndrome Keywords: cell type comparison, disease state analysis, genetic modification

datasets.description_clean: Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Tumor Syndrome type 1 (MEN 1) is an autosomal dominant tumor syndrome affecting individuals with a heterozygous germline mutaion of the MEN1 gene. MEN 1 carriers commonly develop parathyroid, anterior pituitary, duodenal and pancreatic endocrine tumors. The phenotype of existing mouse models for the MEN 1 syndrome, with a germline heterozygous (hz) Men1 gene inactivation, show close resemblance to the human MEN 1 syndrome. Menin, the protein encoded for by the MEN1/Men1 gene, lacks homology with known proteins, and evidence of its involvement in different cellular processes is steadily growing. Several interaction partners have been identified, involving different interaction sites on the menin protein. Accumulating evidence suggests a role for menin in transcriptional regulation, cell cycle control, apoptosis, chromatin modification and DNA damage response and repair. Loss of heterozygosity (LOH) of the MEN1 gene precedes tumor formation in the MEN 1 heterozygous pancreas. We set out to determine if there is a change in gene expression early on in the hz islet, as compared with islets in wildtype (wt) littermates, long before the LOH events occur. We performed a global mRNA expression microarray on islets from young, five-week-old, hz Men1 mice and their wt littermates, and we have subsequently corroborated a subset of the findings on the qPCR and protein level.

datasets.name: omicsADDS
datasets.description_clean: Multiomic Studies of Alzheimer's Disease in Adults with Down Syndrome (omicsADDS) This study aims to identify multi-omic profiles for successful cognitive aging in adults with Down syndrome (DS). Individuals with DS have an increased risk of developing Alzheimer’s disease (AD) with almost all adults with DS presenting sufficient neuropathology for AD by age 40. The elevated risk of AD in this population can be in part attributed to having an extra copy of Chromosome 21 and triplication of the amyloid precursor protein (APP) gene. Yet, the age at onset varies widely with some who might not develop AD at all. This study leverages data from a DS Program Project Study and the corresponding biosamples to contrast these extreme phenotypes to identify multi-omic signatures of relative susceptibility and protection in this cohort with known genetic risk for AD. The recruitment and clinical assessment of the original cohort of adults with Down Syndrome have been detailed in previous publications [1-3]. Study participants who were at least 30 years of age were recruited from New York, New Jersey, Connecticut, and eastern Pennsylvania from state and voluntary service provider agencies. Targeted proteomic, untargeted metabolomic, and genomic data were generated for 472 adults with DS who had donated biosamples for analysis, in conjunction with direct neuropsychological testing and structured informant interviews regarding daily functioning and psychiatric symptoms. Study participants were classified as cognitively-stable (CS), Mild Cognitive Impairment-Down Syndrome (MCI-DS) or Alzheimer’s Disease-Down Syndrome (AD-DS), based on consensus case conference, utilizing all empirical evidence from cognitive and functional assessment of stability or decline to make clinical diagnosis [3].
